        body: "A NAT gateway lets instances in a private subnet reach the internet or other networks without accepting unsolicited inbound connections, and it bills on two dimensions at once — an hourly charge for the gateway itself, plus a per-gigabyte charge for every byte it processes — which makes its placement a real cost decision, not just a redundancy one. A single NAT gateway shared by every private subnet across all Availability Zones in a VPC is the cheapest configuration in hourly terms, but it concentrates all outbound traffic through one AZ, which means instances in other AZs pay cross-AZ data transfer charges on top of the NAT processing charge just to reach it, and it becomes a single point of failure if that AZ has a problem. Deploying one NAT gateway per Availability Zone instead removes both of those costs — no cross-AZ hop for outbound traffic, and no single AZ failure taking down egress for the whole VPC — at the price of paying the hourly charge multiple times over. Running a self-managed NAT instance on EC2 is the older alternative: it avoids the per-gigabyte NAT processing charge entirely, but replaces it with the ongoing cost and operational burden of an EC2 instance that you have to size, patch, and scale yourself, which rarely wins on total cost once the operational overhead is counted honestly.",
