        body: "A VPC peering connection is free to create and carries no charge at all for traffic that stays within a single Availability Zone, which makes it a genuinely no-cost way to connect a small number of VPCs directly — but a peering connection is never transitive, so connecting many VPCs to each other this way requires a full mesh of individual connections that grows quadratically and quickly becomes unmanageable as the VPC count rises, on top of cross-AZ or cross-Region peered traffic still being billed as data transfer. AWS Transit Gateway solves the topology problem by acting as a central routing hub that every VPC, VPN connection, and Direct Connect link attaches to once, replacing that ever-growing mesh with a single hub-and-spoke design and a shared route table — at the cost of an hourly charge per attachment plus a per-gigabyte charge for data it processes, on top of what peering would have cost for the same traffic. For a handful of VPCs, plain peering is close to free and simpler to reason about; past roughly half a dozen VPCs needing to talk to each other and to on-premises networks, a transit gateway's per-attachment cost is usually offset by no longer having to manage (or later untangle) a dense mesh of point-to-point connections, which is the crossover a cost-optimized network design is really weighing.",
